X = insurance[["age"]] #2D data frame
y = insurance["charges"] #1D just one column of ur y
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y)

lr = LinearRegression() #make linear regression function

my_pipeline = Pipeline(
    [('ols', lr)] 
) 

fitted_my_pipeline = my_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)
fitted_my_pipeline

y_preds = fitted_my_pipeline.predict(X_test)
#coefficient estimate of fitted pipeline
fitted_my_pipeline.named_steps['ols'].coef_
array([198.49728308])
#R^2 value
model1_r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_preds)
model1_r2
0.18688016896627846
#mean square error
model1_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_preds)
model1_mse
104276791.21419264
#fit the model
predictions = pd.DataFrame({"X test age": X_test["age"],
                            "y test charges": y_test,
                            "y preds charges": y_preds})

Looking at the plotted model fit, it seems like only using the beneficiaryâs age to predict insurance charges is not enough. The R^2 value is lower than 0.2, and the plot does not take into account the higher charges per age. The mean square error is 107952163.21046798. To interpret the coefficient estimate: For every year older in age, people are billed $207.22 more in medical costs by insurances.

X2 = insurance[["age","sex"]]

enc = OneHotEncoder()

ct = ColumnTransformer(
    [("dummify_sex", enc, ["sex"])]
)

my_pipeline2 = Pipeline(
    [("dummify_everything", ct), ('ols', lr)] 
) 
fitted_my_pipeline2 = my_pipeline2.fit(X_train2, y_train2)

y_preds2 = fitted_my_pipeline2.predict(X_test2)

    [("dummify_smoker", enc, ["smoker"])]
)

my_pipeline3 = Pipeline(
    [("dummify_everything", ct_smoker), ('ols', lr)] 
) 
fitted_my_pipeline3 = my_pipeline3.fit(X_train3, y_train3)

y_preds3 = fitted_my_pipeline3.predict(X_test3)
#R^2 value

#coefficient estimates - it is in alphabetical order
fitted_my_pipeline3.named_steps['ols'].coef_
array([-11565.42806287,  11565.42806287])

The coefficient estimate for nonsmokers and smokers is -11981.34 (female) and 11981.34 (male). The R^2 value is 0.64, and the mean square error is 48090246.933.

#square age and create new column
insurance["age_squared"] = insurance["age"]

X5 = insurance[["age", "age_squared"]]
y5 = insurance["charges"]
X_train5, X_test5, y_train5, y_test5 = train_test_split(X5,y5)

lr = LinearRegression() 
poly2 = PolynomialFeatures(2)

ct2 = ColumnTransformer(
    [("quadratic", poly2, ["age_squared"])]
)

my_pipeline5 = Pipeline(
    [("age_squared", ct2),('ols', lr)] 
) 
fitted_my_pipeline5 = my_pipeline5.fit(X_train5, y_train5)

y_preds5 = fitted_my_pipeline5.predict(X_test5)
#Mean squared error
model5_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test5, y_preds5)
model5_mse
141753265.0126684
#R^2 value
model5_r2 = r2_score(y_test5, y_preds5)
model5_r2
0.09787706054592804

The R^2 value in model 5 is slighly lower than the R^2 value for the model in part 2 question 1. The mean square error in model 5 is also bigger than the mean square error in the model for part 2 question 1.
